==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Woof
<hw>Woof</hw> <pr>(w⟦oomac⟧f)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>oof</ets>, AS. <ets>⟦omac⟧wef</ets>, <ets>⟦omac⟧web</ets>,
<ets>⟦amac⟧web</ets>; <ets>on</ets>, <ets>an</ets>, on + <ets>wef</ets>,
<ets>web</ets>, fr. <ets>wefan</ets> to weave. The initial <it>w</it> is
due to the influence of E. <ets>weave</ets>. See <er>On</er>,
<er>Weave</er>, and cf. <er>Abb</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The threads that cross the warp in a woven fabric;
the weft; the filling; the thread usually carried by the shuttle in
weaving.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Texture; cloth; <as>as, a pall of softest
<ex>woof</ex></as>.</def> <rj><au>Pope.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Woofell</ent>⟦br⟧
